---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import GeneratorShell from '../../components/GeneratorShell.astro';

const title = 'Random Emoji Generator | Genfy';
const description = 'Generate one or many random emojis. Filter by category (faces, animals, food, sports), copy to clipboard and add them to messages or handles.';

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org', '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Where do the emojis come from?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'We use the official Unicode set (15+). Each emoji renders with the user\'s OS font, so it looks identical to WhatsApp, iMessage, Slack and any modern app.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is a random emoji good for?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Creative inspiration, breaking social media block, finding emojis you forgot existed, or just for fun. Some designers use them as prompts for sketches.' } },
    { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does it work on mobile?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Perfectly. Responsive UI and emojis show with the phone\'s native set (Apple on iOS, Google on Android, Samsung on its devices).' } },
  ],
};
---
<Layout title={title} description={description} lang="en" schema={faqSchema} withSidebar={true}>
  <GeneratorShell lang="en" tag="Random" title="Random emoji generator"
    intro="Pick one or many emojis at random. Filter by category, copy with one click, and find emojis you forgot existed.">

    <div slot="tool" class="em-tool">
      <div class="em-controls">
        <div>
          <label for="em-cat">Category</label>
          <select id="em-cat">
            <option value="all" selected>All</option>
            <option value="faces">Faces & emotion</option>
            <option value="hands">Hands & gestures</option>
            <option value="animals">Animals & nature</option>
            <option value="food">Food & drink</option>
            <option value="sport">Activities / sports</option>
            <option value="travel">Travel & places</option>
            <option value="objects">Objects</option>
            <option value="symbols">Symbols</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div>
          <label for="em-count">Count</label>
          <input id="em-count" type="number" value="1" min="1" max="50" />
        </div>
      </div>

      <div id="em-result" class="em-result">🎲</div>

      <div class="em-actions">
        <button id="em-gen" class="btn btn-primary" type="button">Generate emoji(s)</button>
        <button id="em-copy" class="btn btn-ghost" type="button">Copy</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div slot="content">
      <h2>How Unicode standardizes emojis</h2>
      <p>
        Each emoji is a Unicode character (or sequence) with a fixed code point: 🐕 is
        <code>U+1F415</code>, ❤️ is <code>U+2764 U+FE0F</code>. Apple, Google, Samsung,
        Microsoft and Mozilla design their own visual versions, but the character is
        universal: paste an emoji from iPhone to Android and both render the same idea
        in their respective styles. That's how emojis became a global language.
      </p>

      <h2>What random emoji is good for</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Creative inspiration:</strong> illustrators and designers use them as prompts for daily sketches.</li>
        <li><strong>Breaking social media block:</strong> if you can't think how to end a post, a random emoji nudges you in a surprising direction.</li>
        <li><strong>Education:</strong> language games (associate emoji with word), random-element story building.</li>
        <li><strong>List icons:</strong> in docs or slides, a random emoji is more memorable than a bullet point.</li>
        <li><strong>Visual brainstorming:</strong> "design a brand for this combination of three emojis".</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Official Unicode categories</h2>
      <p>
        The standard groups emojis into eight main categories: Smileys & Emotion, People
        & Body, Animals & Nature, Food & Drink, Travel & Places, Activities, Objects,
        Symbols, and Flags. Our tool merges some so the filter stays practical, but it
        respects Unicode ordering internally.
      </p>

      <h2>The world's most-used emoji</h2>
      <p>
        Based on Unicode's annual reports (drawn from Twitter / X and other data),
        consistently most used is 😂 (face with tears of joy), followed by ❤️ and 🥺.
        Apple's "Emoji Day" on July 17 was chosen because that's the date shown on the
        calendar emoji 📅 in iOS. Details that will keep you thinking.
      </p>

      <h2>When NOT to use emojis</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Formal work communications:</strong> in an email to an important client or in a contract, leave them out.</li>
        <li><strong>Serious document typography:</strong> an emoji breaks the visual flow of legal or academic text.</li>
        <li><strong>Senior audiences:</strong> a percentage of people over 60 don't yet read emojis as feelings. Be explicit.</li>
        <li><strong>SEO and URLs:</strong> some browsers support emojis in URLs but search engines handle them inconsistently.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Skin tones and diversity</h2>
      <p>
        Since Unicode 8.0 (2015), people and hand emojis support skin-tone modifiers
        (Fitzpatrick scale). 👋 can be 👋🏻, 👋🏼, 👋🏽, 👋🏾 or 👋🏿. Technique: two code points
        concatenated. Most platforms remember your last preference.
      </p>

      <h2>Technical curiosities</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Some emojis are combinations</strong>: 👨‍👩‍👧‍👦 (family) is 4 individual emojis joined with ZWJ (Zero-Width Joiner) characters. On older systems they show as four separate people.</li>
        <li><strong>The "tofu" 􏿾</strong>: when a system lacks the font for an emoji, it shows an empty square. That's "tofu". Happens with very new emojis on outdated systems.</li>
        <li><strong>Geo-political flags</strong>: Unicode avoids taking sides on territorial disputes, which is why some regions have flags and others don't.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div slot="faq">
      <details><summary>Where do they come from?</summary><p>Official Unicode 15+. Each renders with the OS font (Apple, Google, Samsung).</p></details>
      <details><summary>What is it for?</summary><p>Creative inspiration, breaking blocks, discovering new emojis, visual brainstorming.</p></details>
      <details><summary>On mobile?</summary><p>Yes. Responsive. Renders with the phone's native set.</p></details>
      <details><summary>Filter by category?</summary><p>Yes. 8 categories plus an "all" option.</p></details>
    </div>
  </GeneratorShell>
</Layout>

<style>
  .em-controls { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .em-result { padding: 2.5rem 1.5rem; background: var(--bg-inset); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); border: 1px solid var(--border); text-align: center; font-size: 4rem; line-height: 1.3; word-break: break-word; min-height: 120px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
  .em-actions { display: flex; gap: 0.5rem; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  @media (max-width: 600px) { .em-controls { grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; } .em-result { font-size: 3rem; } }
</style>

